Yes. In Astro MDX, the usual way is to configure global MDX components via `mdx({ components })`, or to use an MDX provider/module setup.

For this project, the cleanest option is likely an MDX components registry file, e.g.

```ts
// src/components/mdx-components.ts
import Figure from './Figure.astro';
import MarginNote from './MarginNote.astro';
import Sidenote from './Sidenote.astro';
import Wikipedia from './Wikipedia.astro';

export const components = {
  Figure,
  MarginNote,
  Sidenote,
  Wikipedia,
};
```

Then wire it into `astro.config.mjs` if Astro’s MDX integration supports the `components` option in the installed version:

```js
import mdx from '@astrojs/mdx';
import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config';

export default defineConfig({
  integrations: [
    mdx({
      components: './src/components/mdx-components.ts',
    }),
  ],
});
```

Then MDX pages can use:

```mdx
<Wikipedia>Monte Carlo</Wikipedia>

<Sidenote>This is a note.</Sidenote>
```

without local imports.

Caveat: exact syntax depends on the Astro/MDX integration version. If that option is unavailable, the fallback is to create a shared import block/snippet or a wrapper layout, but global MDX components are the feature you want.
